During his last illness, Benedict, worn out with travail and with travel, was lying para- lysed on the bed from which he never rose up again3 and there are few more touching scenes, even in Bede, than that in which he tells how the dying Sigfrid was carried into the cell of Benedict, and laid beside him with his head on the same pillow, that so the two friends might take their last farewell of one another in this world 2. ‘In their death they were not divided ' long. Benedict followed his friend on Jan. 12, 689 or 690 ³, having already, with the consent of the brethren, appointed Ceolfrid abbot of both monasteries May 13, 688 01 689 4. He held this post till 716, when, desiring to end his days at Rome, where he had been with Benedict on his fifth visit in 678, 116 resigned, after ruling 1116 11101136161·166 with great devotion and success for about eight and twenty years, and left Wearmouth on June 4, amid the uni- versal grief of the six hundred monks who formed his flock ⁵. Before he finally quitted Britain he was able to confirm the 616011011 of his successor Hwaetbert, who, like Bede himself, had been an inmate of the monastery from his earliest boyhoodss.
